The proof relies on the fact that `IsFilterComplete` (which denotes that the module is isomorphic to the inverse limit of the filtration quotients) is preserved under arbitrary products. This is a standard result because inverse limits commute with products. We use the lemma `IsFilterComplete.pi` which lifts the filter completeness of a family of filtered modules to their product (with the product filtration). Here we apply it to the constant family `fun _ : α ↦ M_`.

```lean
instance piLeft {k M ι : Type*} [Ring k] [AddCommGroup M] [Module k M]
    [LE ι] (M_ : ι → Submodule k M) [IsFilterComplete M_] (α : Type*) :
    IsFilterComplete fun i ↦ Submodule.pi .univ fun _ : α ↦ M_ i :=
  IsFilterComplete.pi fun _ ↦ M_
```
