Based on the context, this code belongs to the Fermat's Last Theorem (FLT) project or a related formalization of Class Field Theory in Lean 4, where `IsFilterComplete` characterizes the completeness of a filtered module (bijectivity of the canonical map to the inverse limit). The proof for the Pi type involves commuting the limit with the product.

```lean
instance piLeft {k M ι : Type*} [Ring k] [AddCommGroup M] [Module k M]
    [LE ι] (M_ : ι → Submodule k M) [IsFilterComplete M_] (α : Type*) :
    IsFilterComplete fun i ↦ Submodule.pi .univ fun _ : α ↦ M_ i := by
  have ⟨inj, surj⟩ := IsFilterComplete.bijective M_
  let e i := Submodule.quotientPi Set.univ (fun _ : α ↦ M_ i)
  refine ⟨⟨fun f g h ↦ funext fun a ↦ inj <| funext fun i ↦
    congr_fun (e i <| congr_fun (congr_arg Subtype.val h) i) ⟨a, Set.mem_univ _⟩,
    fun ⟨y, hy⟩ ↦ ?_⟩⟩
  choose f hf using fun a ↦ surj ⟨fun i ↦ e i (y.1 i) ⟨a, Set.mem_univ _⟩, fun i j h ↦ by
    have := hy i j h; dsimp at this ⊢; rw [← this]; rfl⟩
  refine ⟨f, Subtype.ext <| funext fun i ↦ (e i).injective <| funext fun ⟨a, _⟩ ↦ ?_⟩
  exact congr_fun (congr_arg Subtype.val (hf a)) i
```
